48 SECTION 2.(c) G.S. 20-166 reads as rewritten:
49 "§ 20-166. Duty to stop in event of a crash; furnishing information or assistance to injured
50 person, etc.; persons assisting exempt from civil liability.
51 (a) The driver of any vehicle who knows or reasonably should know:
Page 2 House Bill 246-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) That the vehicle which he or she is operating is involved in a crash; and
2 (2) That the crash has resulted in serious bodily injury, as defined in G.S. 14-32.4,
3 or death to any person;
4 shall immediately stop his or her the driver's vehicle at the scene of the crash. The driver shall
5 remain with the vehicle at the scene of the crash until a law-enforcement officer completes the
6 investigation of the crash or authorizes the driver to leave and the vehicle to be removed, unless
7 remaining at the scene places the driver or others at significant risk of injury.
8 Prior to the completion of the investigation of the crash by a law enforcement officer, or the
9 consent of the officer to leave, the driver may not facilitate, allow, or agree to the removal of the
10 vehicle from the scene for any purpose other than to call for a law enforcement officer, to call
11 for medical assistance or medical treatment as set forth in subsection (b) of this section, or to
12 remove oneself or others from significant risk of injury. If the driver does leave for a reason
13 permitted by this subsection, then the driver must return with the vehicle to the accident scene
14 within a reasonable period of time, unless otherwise instructed by a law enforcement officer. A
15 willful violation of this subsection shall be punished as a Class F felony. Notwithstanding the
16 provisions of G.S. 15A-1340.17, if the crash results in the death of another person, the court shall
17 sentence the defendant in the aggravated range of the appropriate Prior Record Level.
